Yes! Insulation from an agricultural by-product! Carbon storing, energy saving, and oh so cozy.

Straw is one of many amazing solutions: low embodied energy, local, non-toxic ( ideally!), low tech, sculptable, load bearing, fire proof ( especially with a plaster skin), modular, inclusive and it sequesters 60 times the amount of carbon it took to grow it. This is the ‘draw-down’ technology the residential and commercial building sector needs! And it’s code approved!!

Visited a straw built house in Nebraska at Chimney Rock years ago on a film shoot. Owners were amazing characters who had lived there mostly their whole lives. The house was amazingly cool in the summer heat, even without A/C. Have wondered about why we don't utilize a lot of the low-cost proven methods to insulating and building better homes over the years (also see Cosanti in Arizona). My understanding is that Australia is working to end native forest logging partially by shifting the timber production burden over to plantation forests. And while there are plenty of ecosystems that should not be logged (e.g. boreal forests), there are also many that can support careful, long-rotation harvests that rely on natural regeneration. Whereas plantation forests are just big ag but with trees. There needs to be a balance and sustainable innovation on both sides but a blanket ban is neither peak sustainability nor beneficial to any business community other than major corporations.
